---
// Figma file u4NLOVKuXUTKULhSn0sAJQ: eyebrow 1:16966, H1 lines 1:16970/1:16971,
// paragraph 1:16972 (outlined), notice bar 1:16817 (outlined), curves+sparks
// group 1:16398 (Task 1 export), chevron 1:16967. See exact derivations in the
// style block below.
//
// SectionHeading-vs-own-markup decision (required by the Task 2 brief): this
// Hero does NOT consume the new SectionHeading.astro. Evidence: (1) the H1
// (1:16970/1:16971) is 81.3px — a DIFFERENT size from the shared H2 pattern's
// 65px (matches this page's own how-it-works H2, 1:15971) — and is semantically
// the page's <h1>, not an <h2>; (2) the H1 needs two independently-authored
// lines with an inline accent span, a shape SectionHeading's plain-string
// eyebrow + generic H2 slot isn't built for; (3) unlike the how-it-works
// heading, THIS eyebrow has a hairline underline sibling (1:16965) with no
// equivalent in the shared component. This mirrors Home's own precedent: Hero.astro
// there also never used a shared heading component. Only the eyebrow's
// *numeric* treatment is shared (verified identical to SectionHeading's, see
// comments below) — kept as local markup here as the plan's architecture note
// intends ("SectionHeading... used by NEW sections only").
import HeroCurves from "../../assets/initiatives/hero-curves.svg";
import SparkBurstA from "../../assets/initiatives/spark-burst-a.svg";
import SparkBurstB from "../../assets/initiatives/spark-burst-b.svg";
import NoticeIcon from "../../assets/initiatives/notice-icon.svg";
// scroll-arrow: Task 1 found this page's two down-chevron instances (1:16967 here)
// download as byte-identical path data to src/assets/home/scroll-arrow.svg — reuse,
// no separate initiatives asset exists (see init-task-1-report.md).
import ScrollArrow from "../../assets/home/scroll-arrow.svg";
import RevealStar from "../../assets/shared/reveal-star.svg";
---

<section class="hero">
  <div class="orbit" aria-hidden="true">
    <HeroCurves class="curves" />
    <SparkBurstA class="spark spark-a" />
    <SparkBurstB class="spark spark-b" />
  </div>

  <div class="hero-inner reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">INITIATIVES</p>
    <div class="underline" aria-hidden="true"></div>

    <h1>
      <span class="line reveal-line">
        <span class="reveal-line-box">
          <span class="reveal-line-text">Built for <span class="accent">every builder</span></span>
          <RevealStar class="reveal-star" aria-hidden="true" />
        </span>
      </span>
      <span class="line reveal-line">
        <span class="reveal-line-box">
          <span class="reveal-line-text">in India&rsquo;s energy story.</span>
          <RevealStar class="reveal-star" aria-hidden="true" />
        </span>
      </span>
    </h1>

    <p class="lede reveal-rise reveal-rise--after-2-lines">
      Whether you are an early-stage aspiring entrepreneur, a researcher with
      a lab-stage IP, or an institution ready to co-build the next decade of
      energy technology, MC&sup2;+ is for you.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="notice">
    <NoticeIcon class="notice-icon" aria-hidden="true" />
    <p class="notice-text">
      Capital, infrastructure and mentorship support every stage, from lab
      access to pilot sites across the seven energy majors. <a
        href="/support"
        class="notice-link"
        >See the full support stack <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a
      >
    </p>
  </div>

  <ScrollArrow class="scroll" aria-hidden="true" />
</section>

<style>
  .hero {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--color-cream);
    /* padding-top fix (final-review pass, supersedes Task 6's version below):
       Task 6 grew padding-top to close a real dead-space bug (the
       Hero→HowItWorks gap was 381.8px at 1920 vs design's 161.28px) but
       calibrated the growth against the curve's FULL 1107px height — wrong
       anchor. The design's 1920×1107 curve box (node 1:16398) sits at
       canvas y0, i.e. BEHIND the shared header (a full-page Figma capture,
       `figma-initiatives-full-1920.png`, confirms the header's own bottom
       border at pixel row y≈110 and the eyebrow's ink starting at y≈318 —
       both measured in that same full-page canvas). Our live header is
       in-flow (not overlaid), so this section's true content-flow origin
       already starts right where the header ends; sizing min-height off the
       curve's full 1107px (instead of the ~1017px actually visible below the
       header) over-grew padding-top by the header's own height, pushing the
       whole copy stack (eyebrow/H1/lede/notice/chevron) too far down —
       verified: old padding-top put the eyebrow at document y≈406.7px vs the
       live header's own measured height (90.1875px, `getBoundingClientRect`,
       identical at 768–1920) + design target (318px − 90.1875px ≈ 227.8px)
       ≈ 316.5–318px, an ~88–90px overshoot matching the live header's own
       height almost exactly — confirming the double-counted header as the
       root cause. Fix: rebase the same clamp() (below) on
       curve-height-minus-header (1107px − 90.1875px = 1016.8125px =
       63.55rem / 52.96vw) instead of the raw 1107px. The subtracted
       constant (content 726.48px + 64px padding-bottom = 790.48px =
       49.405rem) is unchanged — those child elements didn't move — so this
       remains algebraically the same "grow padding-top only once min-height
       exceeds natural content height" invariant Task 6 established (zero
       dead space when the second branch binds, hence the Hero→HowItWorks
       gap is preserved to <0.01px regardless of which min-height cap is
       used — the cap cancels out of that specific difference). At 1920 this
       now evaluates to 14.145rem (226.32px), landing the eyebrow at
       document y≈316.5px — within 4px of the 318px target — instead of the
       old 406.7px. Below the new crossover (~1674px viewport) max() keeps
       the base 6rem untouched, so 1024/1366 are unaffected (min-height
       still doesn't bind there — verified byte-identical). */
    padding-top: max(6rem, clamp(40rem, 52.96vw, 63.55rem) - 49.405rem);
    padding-bottom: 4rem;
  }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .hero {
      /* Design's own curves box (node 1:16398, hero-curves.svg viewBox) is
         1920x1107, but (see padding-top comment above) that box sits BEHIND
         the shared header in the design's own canvas — only curveHeight
         minus the live header's own rendered height (1107px − 90.1875px =
         1016.8125px) is actually visible below the header in a real page,
         matching Home's own "min-height derived from the band BELOW the
         header" convention (its comment cites "page y110.65 header end" for
         its own header/curve pair; this page's shared header measures
         90.1875px instead — same component, verified via
         getBoundingClientRect, constant across 768–1920). Ratio: 1016.8125 /
         1920 = 52.96vw at the 1920px reference, capped at 1016.8125px =
         63.55rem; 40rem floor is a sanity backstop, not expected to bind at
         any ≥1024px width (same rationale as Home's Hero.astro). */
      min-height: clamp(40rem, 52.96vw, 63.55rem);
    }
  }

  /* Curves + sparks: decorative, absolutely positioned behind copy. Sparks are
     separate sibling nodes (1:16403/1:16404, Task 1 export), positioned as
     percentages of the curves SVG's own 1920x1107 box so they stay locked to
     the curve intersections at any viewport width (same technique as Home's
     Hero.astro and this page's Task 1 report positioning note).
     Vertical offset (final-review fix, pairs with the padding-top/min-height
     fix above): the design's curve box sits at canvas y0, BEHIND the shared
     header (see padding-top comment above — the header's own bottom border
     sits at canvas y≈110 in the full-page reference render). Our live header
     is in normal flow (not overlaid), so `.orbit`'s own top:0 would otherwise
     render canvas y0 starting right at this section's top — i.e. right after
     the header — one header-height too low relative to the design's own
     canvas alignment, and (verified in a real render) it also left the
     curve's OWN full 1107px height poking ~90px past the section's new
     (header-adjusted) bottom edge, `overflow: hidden` slicing clean through
     two live stroke paths rather than cropping only genuine dead space.
     Shifting `.orbit` up by the header's own rendered height re-anchors
     canvas y0 to document y0 (matching the design exactly — verified via
     Figma metadata, node 1:16398's own y≈-7.67, i.e. essentially canvas y0)
     and, since the section's min-height above was independently sized to
     curveHeight-minus-header, now lands the curve's own bottom edge almost
     exactly on the section's bottom edge (zero-crop, no more sliced
     strokes) — confirmed in a render. Sparks are positioned as percentages
     of `.orbit`'s own height (unaffected by this offset), so they stay
     locked to the curve exactly as before. */
  .orbit {
    position: absolute;
    top: -5.6367rem; /* -90.1875px, the shared header's own rendered height (getBoundingClientRect, identical 768–1920) */
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    z-index: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .curves {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }
  .spark {
    position: absolute;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  }
  .spark-a {
    /* node 1:16403: center (1721.06, 560.8) / (1920, 1107) box */
    left: 89.64%;
    top: 50.66%;
    width: 6.323rem; /* 101.17px natural size */
    height: 5.601rem; /* 89.62px */
  }
  .spark-b {
    /* node 1:16404: center (271.84, 849.79) / (1920, 1107) box */
    left: 14.16%;
    top: 76.77%;
    width: 4.609rem; /* 73.75px natural size */
    height: 6.504rem; /* 104.07px */
  }

  .hero-inner {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    /* Node 1:16968 (the H1+lede wrapping group) measures 833.66px = 52.104rem,
       but that's razor-thin against the widest H1 line's own bbox (825px =
       51.5625rem, node 1:16970) — under 9px of slack, which a browser's own
       font shaping tips over into an unwanted wrap (verified: it wrapped at
       52.104rem in a real render). Buffered up to 56rem instead, matching
       AboutHero.astro's own precedent (same buffer-above-widest-line
       technique, same resulting value). */
    max-width: 56rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-inline: 1.25rem; /* narrow-viewport safety only, house convention */
    text-align: center;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0;
    /* Figma reports Faculty Glyphic on this text node (1:16966), but a 6x
       zoomed render (get_screenshot) shows plain sans strokes — no serifs on
       I/N/T/A/V — the same "wrapping-group reports Faculty, rendered glyphs
       are sans" correction already made in Home's Pillars.astro/Audiences.astro.
       Corrected here too (unlike About's AboutHero.astro, which kept Faculty
       for its own eyebrow — verified per-instance, not page-wide; see
       Scale.astro's own note that this file mixes both within one page). */
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-hero-eyebrow); /* 27.07px, node 1:16966 — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    letter-spacing: 0.25em; /* 6.7675px / 27.07px, node 1:16966 */
    color: var(--color-gray); /* #959595 exact match */
  }
  .underline {
    width: 11.77rem; /* 188.25px, node 1:16965 — byte-identical to About's AboutHero.astro underline (1:9500), same construction reused */
    height: 1px;
    margin: 2.8rem auto 1.6rem; /* 45.11px / 26.15px gaps (eyebrow-bottom→underline, underline→H1-top), matching AboutHero's own measurements of this exact construction */
    background: #000; /* one-off literal, matches AboutHero's sampled hairline color (not a token) */
  }

  h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-hero-h1); /* 81.3px, nodes 1:16970/1:16971 — identical to About's AboutHero H1 size — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    line-height: var(--text-hero-h1-lh); /* baseline delta 87.57px (505.25-417.68) / 81.3px = 1.077, same derivation and result as AboutHero.astro — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    color: var(--color-ink-alt); /* #1e1e3c exact match */
  }
  h1 .line {
    display: block;
  }
  h1 .accent {
    color: var(--color-orange); /* #f37d2c exact match, node 1:16970 span fill */
  }

  .lede {
    max-width: 49.2rem; /* 787.27px, the paragraph's own bounding width (node 1:16972) — same technique as AboutHero's lede (its own bbox width used directly as the wrap max-width) */
    margin: 1.5rem auto 0;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    /* Lede (1:16972) is an outlined/vectorized paragraph, not real text, so its
       font-size is re-derived the same way as AboutHero's lede: 3 independent
       glyph heights against the self-hosted Sora font's own metrics
       (src/assets/fonts/Sora-VariableFont_wght.ttf, unitsPerEm 1000, measured
       via fontTools) all converge on the SAME value as AboutHero: the "t"
       ascender height/Sora's own t-ratio (0.702), the "l"/"h" ascender
       height/Sora's l-ratio (0.73), and the cap "C"/Sora's C-ratio (0.768) all
       independently land on ~31px. Line-height, likewise re-derived from the
       4 lines' baseline deltas (~40.5px avg / 31px ≈ 1.31), matches AboutHero's
       lede exactly. */
    font-size: var(--text-hero-lede); /* 31px, derived — see comment above — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    line-height: var(--text-hero-lede-lh); /* derived — see comment above — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    /* Fill sampled directly from this node's own vector paths: #1E1E3C
       (--color-ink-alt) — NOT --color-ink like About's lede (which is a
       DIFFERENT node, #1e1e3a; About's own comment notes this was itself a
       corrected value). Different node, different (if barely distinguishable)
       fill — verify-don't-assume applies per node, not per house pattern. */
    color: var(--color-ink-alt);
  }

  .notice {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1.1rem; /* 17.67px, icon-right-edge to text-left-edge gap, node 1:16817 children */
    max-width: 56rem; /* narrowed from 78.99rem/1263.77px (node 1:16817) per user directive 2026-07-07, to match .hero-inner's own 56rem column above it rather than overshooting it */
    margin: 4.03rem auto 0; /* 64.44px, lede-bottom (785.39) to notice-top (849.83) */
    /* Figma's own node math gives 80.02px here (arrow-right-edge, node 1:16948,
       to pill-right-edge, node 1:16817) — but that reflects the OUTLINED
       vector export's glyph advances, which render ~2% narrower than the same
       live Sora text at the same font-size in a real browser (verified:
       80.02px/5rem here made "See the full support stack" wrap to a 3rd line
       that isn't in the design's own 2-line render). Tightened to the browser-
       verified threshold so the sentence wraps at 2 lines like the design. */
    padding-inline-end: 3rem;
    background: var(--color-ink-alt); /* #1e1e3c, pill fill sampled from node 1:16817's own vector paths */
    border-radius: 999px;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }
  .notice-icon {
    width: 6.8025rem; /* 108.84px — exactly the pill's own height, node 1:16817, flush left with no inset */
    height: 6.8025rem;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .notice-text {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    /* Outlined/vectorized (no real text), re-derived the same way as .lede
       above: 3 independent glyphs from this exact sentence ("C" of "Capital",
       the "t" ascenders, the "l"/"h" ascenders) against Sora's own metrics all
       converge on 28.42px (tighter agreement than .lede's derivation — see
       comment there for method). Line-height from the 2 lines' baseline delta
       (37.1px / 28.42px ≈ 1.31) matches the SAME 1.31 constant as .lede and
       About's lede — a consistent house-wide body-copy line-height regardless
       of font-size. */
    font-size: 1.1463rem; /* 18.34px — notice text was 0.9168× the hero lede in the design (28.42/31); rescaled with the lede: 20px × 0.9168 — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    line-height: 1.31;
    color: var(--color-white); /* sampled fill: literal "white" in the node's own paths */
    text-align: left;
  }
  .notice-link {
    color: var(--color-orange); /* #f37d2c exact match, sampled from this link's own paths */
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: inherit;
  }
  .notice-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .scroll {
    display: block;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    margin: 4.05rem auto 0; /* 64.88px, notice-bottom (958.67) to chevron-top (1023.55), node 1:16967 */
  }

  @media (max-width: 1023.98px) {
    h1 {
      font-size: var(--text-hero-h1-fluid); /* was clamp(2.4rem, 7vw, 5.08rem) — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    }
    .lede {
      max-width: 90%;
    }
    /* Sanctioned adaptation: at ≥1024px the fixed-rem sparks sit precisely on
       the curve intersections (by design), but below 1024px the copy column
       shrinks much less than the curves do, so the sparks drift onto the H1/
       lede text (verified in a real render — spark-a crossed through
       "builder"). Home's own Hero avoids this because its narrower 3-line H1
       leaves more lateral clearance; this page's wider 2-line H1 does not.
       Hiding the sparks (purely decorative, already aria-hidden) below 1024px
       keeps the softer curve lines without the text collision. */
    .spark {
      display: none;
    }
    .notice {
      /* Sanctioned adaptation (design is desktop-only): the wide fixed-width
         pill can't survive a narrow viewport without either truncating or
         overflowing, so it collapses to a stacked card below 1024px — icon
         above text, rounded corners instead of a true pill, full container
         width. */
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: flex-start;
      max-width: 90%;
      border-radius: 1.5rem;
      padding: 1.75rem 1.5rem;
      gap: 1rem;
    }
    .notice-icon {
      width: 3.5rem;
      height: 3.5rem;
    }
  }

</style>
